-- French Stocks Gain, Led by Societe Generale; Vallourec, Vivendi Also Rise
-- Adria Cimino
-- 2010-06-15T16:47:49Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-15/french-stocks-drop-arcelor-dexia-schneider-fall-while-vivendi-advances.html

          
          
             France’s  CAC 40 Index  climbed 35.47,
or 1 percent, to 3,661.51 in Paris.  The SBF 120 Index  also
gained 1 percent.  
 The following shares rose or fell in Paris. Stock symbols
are in parentheses.  
 Euromedis Groupe  (EMG FP) slipped 3.5 percent to 4.11
euros, dropping for a second day. The distributor of medical
supplies said profit this fiscal year will be close to the level
reported for the year ending July 31, 2008.  
 Faiveley Transport  (LEY FP) advanced 2.2 percent to 56.70
euros, gaining for a second day. The railroad-equipment maker
said net income in the year ended March 31 rose 38 percent and
it plans to raise the dividend by 20 percent. Sales this year
will be stable, with a “substantial” increase in following
years, it said.  
 Societe Generale SA  (GLE FP) jumped 3.9 percent to 36.40
euros, gaining for a fifth day. France’s second-biggest bank by
market value said it’s aiming for profit of about 6 billion
euros ($7.3 billion) in 2012, driven by growth at the corporate
and investment bank and in Russia.  
 Vallourec SA  (VK FP), a maker of steel pipes for the oil
and gas industry, rallied 1.3 percent to 149.25 euros. Crude oil
for July delivery rose as much as 2.1 percent to $76.70 on the
New York Mercantile Exchange.  
 Vivendi SA  (VIV FP), owner of Universal Music Group, gained
1.8 percent to 17.85 euros, climbing for a fifth day. Global
music sales are approaching a turning point as revenue from
digital outlets such as Apple Inc.’s iTunes overtake purchases
of CDs, according to a PricewaterhouseCoopers report. Spending
on recorded music will increase to $27.9 billion in 2014, from
$26.4 billion last year, according to the report.  
